<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-878-968  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 878 968.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Nov 13 1989 v6 n45 p2(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Study says power of EDI untapped by many users. (electronic datainterchange)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study conducted by the Gallup Organization, for EDI ResearchInc, which was titled 'The State of U.S.andP;  EDI: 1989,' reveals thatdespite the promise of electronic data interchange (EDI), mostcompanies have not yet implemented the technology.andP;  The studyshows that less than one quarter of companies surveyed will beusing EDI by the end of 1989 and that only 6 percent plan toimplement the technology in 1990.andP;  The study indicates that EDIuse is growing, being driven by a few large companies that arepushing their trading partners to adopt the technology.andP;  Barriersto establishing EDI with trading partners include the lack ofcompatible software, hardware or EDI formats; unwilling tradingpartners; and unsatisfactory cost-benefit analyses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   EDI Research Inc. (surveys)Gallup Organization Inc. (surveys).andO;Topic:     Electronic Data InterchangeUser SurveyForecastingImplementationReports.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   EDI use at Fortune 1,000 firms. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>